With 5 volt sensors you would follow this

FIRST Robotics Competition Documentation

Proximity Switches - Hardware

One of the most common sensing tasks on a robot is detecting when an object (be it a mechanism, game piece, or field element) is within a certain distance of a known point on the robot. This type o...

Brown = 5V
L = GND
White or Black for S either works the on off condition is just opposite
Unfortunately, that sensor requires a voltage between 10 and 30 volts to operate.
It is possible but suggest you check this thread Beam Break Sensor Questions - #3 by Strategic and find a 5 volt unit.

This sensor should work for you as is without complicated resistors or 5V reduction. NPN switches the ground not the high voltage thus the 12 v supply to operate the sensor is not gong into the 5v limited DIO. You might be able to match your schematic with the ones in the attached paper I put together.
DigitalInput Including PhotoElectric Proximity Switch Connection to roboRIO DIO.doc (71 KB)
(Hope you can read .doc since Google drive somewhat trashed the .pdf export.)
